data.name: Textbox_TcJoyUpdateRate.ToolTip
data.value: The TcJoy Update Rate is the rate with which TcJoy updates itself. Lower values will cause faster response times, but draw more Power. Higher values will cause slower response times, but draw less Power.

data.name: TextBox_AnalogDeadzone.ToolTip
data.value: The Analog Sticks of the Controller are not showing Zeros when there's no input. To account for this imperfection you may set an Analog Stick Dead Zone here. Values between 6000 and 8000 work well.

data.name: TextBox_ADSWatchdogDeadDuration.ToolTip
data.value: In the event of a Watchdog timeout due to network or controller loss while in operation, this timer is how long the outputs will be held at 0. This is important so the user has time to realize they lost control and let off the inputs to avoid unexpected machine motion.

data.name: TextBox_ADSWatchdog.ToolTip
data.value: If no updates make it to the PLC for this amount of time, the PLC will null the outputs to stop machine motion ASAP. Put this as large as you are comfortable, but the larger it is, the longer the delay will be before the outputs are cut on the PLC side, so keep it just larger than the ADS rate, but hopefully rather small still. For an ADS Rate of 100ms the Watchdog should be no higher than 200ms.

data.name: TextBox_TcJoyPath.ToolTip
data.value: This is the instance path of the user-created instance of FB_TcJoy on the PLC Runtime. I usually put it in global so multiple parts of the code can read the values they want to use for remote control. Note on TC3, the default is GVL instead of Global_Variables. If you have this wrong, when you connect up to the PLC you'll get an error.

data.name: TextBox_ADSRate.ToolTip
data.value: The ADS Rate is the rate at which the data will be sent to the PLC over ADS. Lower values will cause faster response times, but draw more Power. Higher values will cause slower response times, but draw less Power. 20ms is about the max you should do here, but 100ms is 10 times a second, which is typically plenty fast.

data.name: TextBox_ADSNetID.ToolTip
data.value: Every PC on the network can be uniquely identified by a TCP/IP address, such as "172.1.2.16". The AdsAmsNetId is an extension of the TCP/IP address and identifies a TwinCAT message router, e.g. "172.1.2.16.1.1". TwinCAT message routers exist on every TwinCAT PC, and on every Beckhoff BCxxxx bus controller (e.g. BC3100, BC8100, BC9000, ...).

data.name: TextBox_ADSPort.ToolTip
data.value: The ADS devices in a TwinCAT message router are uniquely identified by a number referred to as the ADS-PortNr. For ADS devices this has a fixed specification, whereas pure ADS client applications (e.g. a visualisation system) are allocated a variable ADS port number when they first access the message router.

data.name: RichTextBox_Help.Text
data.value: To use this, connect up an XBOX wireless controller. Make an instance of FB_TcJoy, preferably in gloabl variables so you don't have to create a custom path. Connect to the PLC, and then use the output variables to poke into anything in your machine you want. They will drop to 0 / False if the controller or the ADS link goes away. See the TcJoy Github page for more information: https://github.com/evanmj/TcJoy Also please consider donating, all proceeds will go to my children's college fund: https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=8YQRPBYQVAJ36&source=url
